Crude Oil Volatility Surges as Futures Drop to Eight-Month Low

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-08-08T19:55:45Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-08/crude-oil-volatility-surges-as-futures-drop-to-eight-month-low.html
Oil options volatility surged as
futures tumbled to the lowest price in more than eight months
after  Standard & Poor’s  downgraded the U.S.’s credit rating for
the first time.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
September, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options prices, was 68.7 percent at 3 p.m. in  New York ,
up from 40.9 percent Aug. 5.  Oil for September delivery dropped $5.57, or 6.4 percent,
to settle at $81.31 a barrel on the  New York Mercantile
Exchange . Prices have fallen 11 percent this year.  The most active contracts in electronic trading today were
September $75 puts, with 6,156 lots changing hands at 3:55 p.m.
They gained $1.15 to $1.36 a barrel. September $80 puts, the
next-most active option, increased $2.15 to $2.80 a barrel with
3,862 lots trading. One contract covers 1,000 barrels of crude.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information on floor trading, where the
bulk of options trading occurs, the next business day.  September $80 puts were the most active options traded in
the previous session, with 10,974 lots changing hands. They
retreated 13 cents to 65 cents a barrel. The next-most active
options, December $80 puts, slipped 3 cents to $3.55 on volume
of 10,767.  Open interest was highest for December $120 calls with
44,715 contracts. Next were December $100 calls with 43,991 and
December $80 puts with 43,928.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in Dallas at 
